Cli\u003EDoes not engage in pretend play\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EShows minimal interest in other children\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the age by which these skills should normally be achieved?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["One year","18 months","Two years","Three years","Four years"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBy \u003Cstrong\u003Ethree years\u003C/strong\u003E of age, children should typically be able to ascend stairs alternating feet, copy a circle, engage in pretend play, and show interest in playing with peers. Absence of these skills at this age warrants developmental assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe developmental skills mentioned would be too advanced for a child aged \u003Cstrong\u003Eone year\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E18 months\u003C/strong\u003E. At \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo years\u003C/strong\u003E, children are still developing these abilities. By \u003Cstrong\u003Efour years\u003C/strong\u003E, children should have mastered these skills and be achieving more advanced milestones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey developmental milestones for a three-year-old include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGross motor: Climbing stairs alternating feet, riding a tricycle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFine motor: Copying a circle, using utensils\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESocial: Engaging in pretend play, playing alongside other children\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELanguage: Speaking in short phrases, following two-step commands\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["By age 3 years, children should be able to climb stairs alternating feet, copy a circle, engage in pretend play, and show interest in peers.","Gross motor, fine motor, and social development milestones 